docs.abstract: Leaders from Oxfam, Microsoft, the Ad Council and more discussed sexual harassment, gender power dynamics and styles of leadership at the World Economic Forum.
docs.snippet: Leaders from Oxfam, Microsoft, the Ad Council and more discussed sexual harassment, gender power dynamics and styles of leadership at the World Economic Forum.
docs.lead_paragraph: Looking back on nearly three decades in the tech sector, Peggy Johnson recalled how she and other women used to steer clear of leering colleagues by taking the long way to their desks, and how they felt pressured to laugh at inappropriate jokes in the office.

headline.main: ‘She’s Not Laughing’: In Davos, Taking on Sexual Harassment

docs.lead_paragraph: The first two things you notice when you walk into Bill Gates’s private office, just outside Seattle, are a wall-size installation of the periodic table with a sample of each chemical element in its own glass-fronted vitrine and handsome bookshelves that reach nearly to the ceiling.

headline.main: The Mind Meld of Bill Gates and Steven Pinker

docs.abstract: Hackers can exploit two major security flaws in microprocessors running virtually all machines on Earth. What do you do now?
docs.snippet: Hackers can exploit two major security flaws in microprocessors running virtually all machines on Earth. What do you do now?
docs.lead_paragraph: On Wednesday, a group of security experts revealed two security flaws that affect nearly all microprocessors, the digital brains of the world’s computers. These flaws, called Meltdown and Spectre, could allow hackers to lift passwords, photos, documents and other data from smartphones, PCs and the cloud computing services that many businesses rely on.

headline.main: What You Need to Do Because of Flaws in Computer Chips
headline.print_headline: The Lowdown on the Flaws in Computer Chips
